&quot;People will travel less and less,&quot; says Phillipe De Vreyer, Parisian expert on West Africa&#39;s economy.
For example, the man who usually goes to the market and sells his vegetables prefers to stay at home.
The population is therefore feeling the consequences of the epidemic directly and urgently: food is becoming scarce.
The markets are running out of staple foods like rice.
At the same time, the region, which is heavily dependent on international companies, is threatened with image damage - with far-reaching consequences.
The greatest danger is that international companies generally avoid the area for a long time, says Philippe Hugon from the French think tank Iris.
The decisive factor is how far and how long the virus will spread.
Investors could get the impression &quot;that it&#39;s dangerous to live in Guinea, Sierra Leone and Liberia and therefore also to invest,&quot; warns Hugon.
The disease is also taking a toll on states&#39; strained national budgets
The disease also burdens the already strained national budgets of the affected countries.
The rating agency Moody&#39;s fears that their budgets will be severely strained by the high expenditures for the health care system and additionally by the deteriorating economy.
The African Development Bank has already promised to help the affected countries&#39; health systems with $60 million (€45 million).
The effects are already being felt in Nigeria, where only a few Ebola cases have been diagnosed to date.
The oil-rich region in the southern Niger Delta has not been affected so far.
But elsewhere, many people are already staying at home for fear of infection.
Reservations in hotels are also falling significantly.
