Under this treetop there is peace
We showed a mighty trunk in our puzzle task of the summer series &quot;My Piece of Rhöner Glück&quot; last Friday.
There are still several of these giant trees in the district, the example shown is the &quot;Geißruheiche&quot; above Unterweißenbrunn.
A bumpy footpath leads up to the approximately 600-year-old oak tree.
It goes past paddocks, basalt rock piles and basalt rock seas.
A little below the Bauersberg quarry, a kilometer north of the road to Weisbach, there it is.
The natural monument looks vital, it towers above the other trees in the area and, with a circumference of over eight meters, is reminiscent of an American sequoia.
A small Buddha on a tree stump indicates that it is a spiritual or mystical place.
But despite intensive research, there were only indications of the origin of the name.
dr Wolfgang Schneider specifically consulted the Bischofsheim archive and interviewed older people from Unterweißenbrunn to find out what happened to the goat oak.
The result of his research remained the rather sober explanation for the name.
According to this, the goatherds are said to have driven their animals from Unterweißenbrunn to the laboriously cleared and stone-free meadows up until about 80 years ago.
At the foot of the tree, the animal keepers, exhausted from the ascent, are said to have rested.
In the meantime, the area has regained its importance, because herds of goats are actually grazing on the meadows again.
The area has also been declared a core zone of the biosphere reserve, Schneider further found out.
However, one should exercise caution when entering the stone accumulations, because the basalt, which has been warmed up by the sun, is also a popular place for adders.
A hiking trail leads from Unterweißenbrunn to the tree, which is somewhat hidden.
Other paths are signposted that climb towards the Hochrhön and invite you to take a long hike.
Where is the moated castle?
A moated castle, which is what we are looking for in our next task, is rarely found at this height.
The reflection in the ditch already gives a good impression of the building, but we have some historical buildings in the district that the picture of the building could match.
Where is our &quot;piece of Rhöner Glück&quot; located?
My piece of Rhön happiness
