After weeks of tug-of-war, Italy&#39;s prime minister and incumbent EU chairman, Matteo Renzi, pushed through the nomination of his foreign minister Federica Mogherini as head of EU foreign policy against strong conservative resistance at the EU special summit last week. She will succeed Britain&#39;s Catherine Ashton.
As the pro-government daily La Repubblica reports, Renzi sees the appointment of his Mogherini, who is also a favorite in the government team, as strengthening the position of the Social Democrats and his own in the EU.
He also expects this to give a boost to his &quot;package of reforms&quot; in Italy.
Last but not least, Renzi hopes to pacify the left-wing base of the party, which keeps protesting against him, because Mogherini is associated with him, albeit in a more moderate way.
The prevailing opinion in Rome was that a political balance was being struck with the conservative representatives, Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and Poland&#39;s Donald Tusk, who was nominated as Council President.
Because the EU&#39;s chief diplomat will also be deputy to Commission President Juncker.
The pending approval of the EU Parliament is considered certain.
Otherwise President Giorgio Napolitano would hardly have called the nomination of the 41-year-old politician from the ruling Democratic Party (PD) an &quot;important recognition&quot; of Italy&#39;s role in the EU.
La Repubblica is spreading optimism that Mogherini, who has held leading party offices for almost two decades and is known for her ambition, will show herself equal to the &quot;enormous challenges&quot;.
Born in Rome, she is married and has two daughters.
The doctor of political science began her party career in 1996 in the youth organization of the former Democratici di Sinistra (Left Democrats), which merged with the Catholic center party Margherita in 2008 to form today&#39;s social democratic PD.
In 1999, Mogherini became Vice President of the European Community Organization of Socialist Youth for three years.
When she was elected to the party council of the Left Democrats in 2001, she entered high party politics and worked in the foreign policy department, of which she soon became head.
She occupied traditional focal points of Italian foreign policy such as the Middle East, became known through studies on the NATO mission in Afghanistan, in which Italy is involved with a contingent of troops, and maintained contacts with the Social Democrats in Europe and the Democrats in the USA.
She has been a member of the Chamber of Deputies since 2008, where she is an expert on defense and European and international affairs.
When Renzi became prime minister in February 2014, he appointed Mogherini as his foreign minister.
If the PD now has a better relationship with the strong peace movement in the country, which contributed to the party&#39;s more than 40 percent votes in the EU elections in May, then, as PD circles note, Federica Mogherini has a part to play.
The allegations in Brussels that the new EU foreign policy chief has too little diplomatic experience, and therefore lacks substance, are countered in the PD.
In Brussels, especially by Poland and the Baltic members, Mogherini&#39;s realistic accents on the crisis in Ukraine are suspiciously followed and defamed as a &quot;Russia-friendly course&quot;.
She supports the South Stream pipeline, operated by the Russian company Gazprom, through which Russian natural gas is to be transported directly to southern Europe bypassing Ukraine, which also serves to secure Italy&#39;s energy supply.
After Renzi took office as EU President in July, Mogherini made her first state visit to Moscow.
Photos showing her shaking hands with Putin were met with outrage in Brussels, as was the fact that she invited the Kremlin boss to a Milan economic summit in October.
