Norwegian Cruise on the verge of a $3 billion deal with Prestige Cruises
Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings Ltd NCHL.O, the world&#39;s third largest cruise operator, is in advanced negotiations to acquire competitor Prestige Cruises International Inc for about $3 billion, according to industry insiders.
A deal would give Norwegian Cruise, a company with a market value of $6.8 billion, access to Prestige Cruises&#39; luxury cruise lines and its affluent clientele, while dealing with larger rivals like Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd (RCL.N) and Carnival Corp (CCL.N) is in competition.
An agreement could be announced as early as this week, the sources said on Sunday, warning that the talks could end inconclusively.
Prestige Cruises&#39; owner, private equity firm Apollo Global Management LLC (APO.N), also owns a 20 percent stake in Norwegian Cruise.
The sources asked to remain anonymous as the negotiations are not public.
Representatives for Norwegian Cruise and Prestige Cruises did not respond to requests for comment, while a spokesman for Apollo declined to comment.
Miami-based Norwegian Cruise operates 13 cruise ships on routes between North America, the Mediterranean, the Baltic Sea, Central America and the Caribbean.
Its 2013 revenue was $2.57 billion, a 13 percent increase over 2012.
Prestige Cruises, also based in Miami, operates under the Oceania and Regent brands, which together operate eight cruise ships on routes to Scandinavia, Russia, the Mediterranean, North America, Asia, Africa and South America.
It reported revenue of $1.2 billion for 2013, up 6 percent from the previous year.
The cruise industry as a whole is about $29 billion and is expected to grow in the next few years due to the strengthening of the middle class in emerging markets like China and India.
The companies are trying to position themselves as the best choice among cruise operators for these new customers.
Prestige Cruises filed for an IPO with US regulators in January 2014.
Apollo has been the majority shareholder in the company since an $850 million deal in 2007.
Norwegian Cruise was formed in its current form in 2000 through a merger with a cruise operator owned by Genting Bhd (GENT.KL), a leisure and casino conglomerate controlled by Malaysian billionaire Lim Kok Thay.
Apollo invested $1 billion in Norwegian Cruise in 2008.
Norwegian Cruise went public in January 2013.
Genting held 28 percent of the shares, Apollo held 20 percent of the shares and private equity firm TPG Capital LP held an 8 percent stake in the company at the end of June, according to regulatory authorities.
Carnival, Royal Caribbean Cruises and Norwegian Cruise together control 82 percent of the passenger capacity on American cruise lines, according to Prestige Cruises&#39; original IPO offering documents.
