Putin is demanding that Kiev start &quot;statehood talks&quot; with eastern Ukraine
According to Russian media reports, Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded on Sunday that the Ukrainian government stop fighting the separatists in the east of the country and immediately start negotiations on the &quot;statehood&quot; of the breakaway region.
His spokesman, Dmitry Peskov, later clarified that Putin did not mean that the separatist-controlled area of eastern Ukraine would become part of Russia, but that his status vis-à-vis Ukraine would have to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region power to to represent his rights and interests.
However, Putin&#39;s call for the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents fits in with the strategy he appears to have been pursuing since the riots began five months ago: helping the separatists seize territories and pressuring the Ukrainian government to to allow the newly proclaimed region of Novorossiya de facto independence for an alliance with Russia rather than with the West.
In an interview with state-run Channel One television, Putin condemned Ukraine&#39;s military campaign to retake separatist-held areas in the eastern Donetsk and Luhansk regions, taken in March and April after Moscow annexed Ukraine&#39;s Crimea peninsula on March 18.
The Kremlin and separatists have recently dubbed the captured territory &quot;Novorossiya&quot; or &quot;New Russia,&quot; a term evoking the pre-revolutionary heyday of the Russian Empire.
Putin pointed out that all those hoping for peace talks in the wake of Ukrainian politicians&#39; campaigns for Oct. 26 elections and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in separatist-held areas are &quot;trapped in their illusions,&quot; Itar reported - cup
&quot;We must immediately start detailed talks, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of south-eastern Ukraine in order to protect the interests of the people living there,&quot; he said.
Peskov said Putin&#39;s reference to statehood must be seen in the context of greater autonomy, which the Kiev leadership has been discussing for months to allay fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are at risk.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern regions, Peskov said.
This isn&#39;t about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, &quot;because it&#39;s not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, it&#39;s about an internal conflict in Ukraine.&quot;
The Kremlin spokesman&#39;s clarification to correct the &quot;misreading&quot; of Putin&#39;s remarks underscored Russia&#39;s leadership claim in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the east, as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, where the majority of the 2 million residents are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions of eastern Ukraine, given that most of the country&#39;s 6.5 million residents are non-Russian and pre-conflict polls showed a large majority to remain in Ukraine.
The autonomy, which has been raised by Russian diplomats at international fora, would give regional governments in Ukraine full powers to negotiate their own trade deals and foreign relations, giving the Kremlin de facto control over an area that shares Russian territory with Crimea connects.
Annexed five months ago, the Black Sea peninsula is the home port for most of the Russian Navy, as well as a major trading port and historical coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko, during his inauguration speech on June 7, suggested that the Ukrainian legislature - after new elections - consider amendments to the constitution that give the respective regions greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his vision of autonomy appears to be in sharp contrast to those of the Kremlin and the Separatist rebels whom Moscow is accused of arming and inciting.
